'''Peter Budaj''' (born September 18, 1982) is a [[Slovaks|Slovak]] professional [[ice hockey]] [[goaltender]] currently playing for the [[Montreal Canadiens]] of the [[National Hockey League]] (NHL).

==Playing career==
Budaj was drafted by the Colorado Avalanche in the [[2001 NHL Entry Draft|2001 draft]] as the first pick for the Avalanche and 63rd overall. He wears number 31 for the Avalanche prior to playing for the [[Hershey Bears]] of the [[American Hockey League]] (AHL) and the [[Toronto St. Michael's Majors]] of the [[Ontario Hockey League]] (OHL). 

[[File:PeterBudaj.jpg|left|thumb|Budaj with the [[Colorado Avalanche|Avalanche]] in [[2007-08 NHL season|2007]].]]
In his first NHL season in [[2005<U+2013>06 NHL season|2005<U+2013>06]], he appeared in 34 games while backing up [[David Aebischer]] and then [[Jos<U+00E9> Th<U+00E9>odore]]. He recorded a combined 47 wins in the next two seasons while splitting duties with Th<U+00E9>odore. His first NHL playoff appearances came in the [[2008 Stanley Cup Playoffs]] in relief of Th<U+00E9>odore in Colorado's second round matchup against the eventual [[Stanley Cup]] champions [[Detroit Red Wings]].

Budaj played his 100th NHL game on November 3, 2007, in a 4-3 home loss against the [[Vancouver Canucks]].<ref>{{cite news |title =Game Recap - Canucks 4, Avalanche 3|url =http://www.nhl.com/nhl/app?service=page&page=Recap&gameNumber=197&season=20072008&gameType=2|author =[[Associated Press]]|publisher =[[National Hockey League|NHL]]|date =2007-11-03|accessdate =2007-11-04}} {{Dead link|date=October 2010|bot=H3llBot}}</ref>

For the [[2008<U+2013>09 NHL season|2008<U+2013>09]] season, Budaj was named the starting goalie for the Colorado Avalanche for the first time. He and backup goaltender [[Andrew Raycroft]] struggled throughout the season as the Avalanche finished last in the Western Conference, missing the playoffs for the second time in last three seasons.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nhl.com/ice/news.htm?id=418201#&navid=nhl-search|title=Avalanche GM Giguere pays price for poor season | publisher =nhl.com | date = 2009-04-13 | accessdate = 2009-04-20}}</ref>

On June 29, 2009, Budaj was re-signed by the Avalanche to a one-year contract for the [[2009<U+2013>10 NHL season|2009<U+2013>10]] season.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/avalanche/ci_12718821|title=Budaj signs deal, likely No. 2 in net | publisher =denverpost.com | date = 2009-06-30 | accessdate = 2009-06-30 | first=Adrian | last=Dater}}</ref>  He started the season playing as the Avalanche backup goalie to [[Craig Anderson (ice hockey)|Craig Anderson]], formerly of the [[Florida Panthers]]. Before his first appearance in net, Budaj was diagnosed with the [[H1N1 virus]] and was completely isolated from the rest of the team until he was cleared to play by the coaching staff.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/avalanche/ci_13651766|title=Swine flu fells Avalanche goalie Peter Budaj | publisher =''[[The Denver Post]]'' | date = 2009-10-27 | accessdate = 2010-01-01 | first=Terry | last=Frei}}</ref> Budaj finally made his first appearance of the season on November 4, against the [[Phoenix Coyotes]]. He stopped 28 of 29 shots and backstopped the Avs to a 4-1 victory.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.cbssports.com/nhl/gamecenter/recap/NHL_20091104_PHO@COL?tag=pageRow;pageContainer|title=Back from swine flu, Budaj gets death in first start of season for Avs | publisher =''[[CBS Sports]]'' | date = 2009-11-04 | accessdate = 2010-04-25}}</ref> Budaj made his second post season appearance on April 22, 2010 against the [[San Jose Sharks]], when he relieved Craig Anderson at 11:05 in the third period. The Sharks won the game 5-0, with one goal scored against Budaj.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.boston.com/sports/hockey/articles/2010/04/23/nabokov_couture_lead_sharks_to_5_0_win_over_avs/|title=Nabokov, Couture lead Sharks to 5-0 win over Avs | publisher =boston.com | date = 2010-04-22 | accessdate = 2010-04-22}} {{Dead link|date=September 2010|bot=RjwilmsiBot}}</ref>

On April 1, 2011, Budaj became the first Slovakian goaltender to reach 100 career NHL wins with a 4-3 shootout win over Phoenix.

Budaj signed a two-year contract worth $2.3 million with the [[Montreal Canadiens]] on July 1, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|title=NHL Free Agent Tracker|url=http://www.tsn.ca/nhl/feature/?id=25880|work=The Sports Network|accessdate=1 July 2011}}</ref>

==Mask==
Budaj, a devout Christian, is perhaps best known for having the depiction of [[Ned Flanders]], a popular religious character from TV's [[The Simpsons]] painted on the back of his masks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/avalanche/ci_16560348|title=Faith is just one goal for Avs' Budaj | publisher =denverpost.com | date = 2010-11-09 | accessdate = 2010-11-28 | first=Adrian | last=Dater}}</ref> In 2008, Budaj began wearing a mask featuring the character [[Alta<U+00EF>r]] from the popular video game [[Assassin's Creed]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.denverpost.com/avsmailbag/ci_11001171?source=rss|title=Mailbag: Man behind the Mask | publisher =denverpost.com | date = 2008-11-17 | accessdate = 2009-04-20 | first=Adrian | last=Dater}}</ref>
The mask primarily worn by Budaj during the 2008<U+2013>09 season features a burgundy colored version of the comic book hero [[Hulk (comics)|The Hulk]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://msn.foxsports.com/nhl/story/8864426/AVALANCHE-Budaj-getting-swagger-back-in-his-game-|title=Budaj getting swagger back into his game | publisher =foxsports.com | date = 2008-03-20 | accessdate = 2009-01-10}}</ref> although he did continue wearing the Assassin's Creed mask as well.  Budaj's 2009<U+2013>10 mask features his racing idol [[Valentino Rossi]] on one side, the Avalanche's alternate foot logo on the other, and retains Ned Flanders on the back.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://ingoalmag.com/masks/peter-budajs-2009-2010-colorado-avalanche-mask/ |title=Peter Budaj<U+2019>s 2009-2010 Colorado Avalanche Mask |author=David Hutchison |date=11 October 2009 |accessdate=5 November 2009}}</ref>

==Personal life==
Peter and his wife Taylor have one son; Peter Jr., who was born in July 2010.<ref>http://avalanche.nhl.com/v2/ext/PDF/MediaGuide_1011_17-41.pdf</ref>

==Awards & achievements==
*2001<U+2013>02  [[Ontario Hockey League|OHL]]  Second All-Star Team
*2006<U+2013>07  [[NHL YoungStars Game]]

